50|$|The {{publication}} of Unsafe at Any Speed by Ralph Nader in 1965 {{gave rise to}} a new type of legal-focused, anti-corporate activism. Whereas past activism had focused on the consequences of consumer actions and <b>the</b> <b>protection</b> <b>of</b> <b>consumers,</b> Lang and Gabriel argue the activism inspired by Ralph Nader and others is more confrontational toward the market. From the 1990s and into the 21st century, consumer activism has been closely associated with sharp critiques of globalization and the damaging effects of concentrated corporate power.|$|E
